ProMED-ESP]
<http://www.reforma.com/nacional/articulo/303516/default.htm>

Threat of outbreak of cutaneous anthrax minimized
-------------------------------------------------
The Governor of Michoacan, Lazaro Cardenas Batel, has stated that there is
no risk that the outbreak of skin anthrax detected in a community of that
state will propagate to the rest of the population. It is not a large
outbreak and there is no cause for alarm as it has been confirmed that the
individuals affected acquired the infection through contact with a dead animal.
Cardenas Batel further explained that this is not pulmonary anthrax, which
can cause serious illness and death in some people, but a perfectly
controllable and limited type of [cutaneous] anthrax. The state health
department reported that the 4 victims registered are in stable condition
in hospitals of Morelia and Patzcuaro. Cardenas Batel confirmed that the
outbreak originated in the community of Santa Rita, in the municipality of
Salvador Escalante.
According to the official report, the host animal was a calf that was
skinned by 6 members of 2 local families. Until 17 June, 4 people,
including one woman, presented symptoms of skin anthrax [Onset of the first
case was Sat 14 Jun 2003, according to an earlier report. - Mod.JW]
The governor insisted that, of course, there is cause for concern and that
the situation must be addressed, but that it is not an alarming case. The
state authorities have already reported the outbreak to Mexico's health
secretary, Julio Frenk Mora. State health workers visited the area where
the outbreak originated and confirmed that there are no additional cases of
infection.
The most severe case is a 44 year old man who had to undergo surgery to
restore blood circulation in his right arm. The procedure was performed in
the Hospital Civil de Morelia. The other patients are between 22 and 27
years old and remain under observation in private hospitals.
[byline: Adan Garcia/Grupo Reforma]
